U.S. stock indexes midday Tuesday were trading sharply lower, led by declines in information technology and communication services shares. The Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, +0.61% was off 672 points, or 2.9%, at 22,981, at last check, while the S&P 500 index SPX, +0.27% was down 3.2% at 2,732, while the Nasdaq Composite Index COMP, +0.52% was trading 3.7% lower at 8,243. Losses in tech names were being leading the way down and powered by a retreat in Amazon.com Inc. AMZN, -0.15%, down 3.1% , and shares of Tesla Inc. TSLA, +4.18%, which were off 7.4%. A decline in shares of iPhone maker Apple Inc. AAPL, +0.08%, Microsoft Corp. MSFT, -0.13% and International Business Machines IBM, -0.25% was dragging the Dow sharply lower. Only one component of the 30 in the blue-chip index was trading higher and that was insurer Travelers Cos. Inc. TRV, +1.05%, up a 2.2%. 